\begin{abstract}
We extend the Hamiltonian crystal framework by embedding the nontrivial zeros of the Riemann zeta function as operators in Fock-space. This introduces logarithmically spaced energy corrections in the vacuum and particle sectors. We derive explicit expressions for the first few Riemann zeros, link them to observable deviations in neutrino oscillations and vacuum energy, and provide concrete experimental predictions for upcoming detectors such as DUNE. 
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
The Hamiltonian crystal framework models the vacuum as a discrete lattice of Fock-space modes with spectral gaps $\Delta E_n$. \textbf{Time-crystalline effects}, \textbf{portal couplings}, and \textbf{dark-sector interactions} produce small, calculable deviations in observables. We now incorporate a \textbf{Riemann-zero operator} $\hat{\mathcal{R}}$ that encodes the nontrivial zeros of the Riemann zeta function $\zeta(s)$, providing an elegant link between number theory and particle physics.

\section{Riemann-Zero Operator in Fock-Space}
Define the operator $\hat{\mathcal{R}}$ acting on lattice mode $|n\rangle$:
\begin{equation}
\hat{\mathcal{R}} |n\rangle = \gamma_n |n\rangle, \quad \zeta\left(\frac{1}{2} + i\gamma_n\right) = 0,
\end{equation}
where $\gamma_n$ are the imaginary parts of the nontrivial Riemann zeros. In the Hamiltonian crystal, we introduce a perturbation:
\begin{equation}
H_{\rm crystal}^{(\mathcal{R})} = H_{\rm crystal} + \epsilon \sum_n \gamma_n a_n^\dagger a_n,
\end{equation}
with $\epsilon \ll \Delta E_n$ controlling the magnitude of the Riemann-induced shifts.

\section{Corrections to Particle Spectra}
The modified energies are
\begin{equation}
E_n^{(\mathcal{R})} = E_n + \epsilon \gamma_n.
\end{equation}
For neutrino oscillations between flavors $\alpha$ and $\beta$, the oscillation phase becomes
\begin{equation}
\Delta \phi_{\alpha\beta} = \frac{\Delta m^2_{\alpha\beta} L}{2 E} + \frac{\epsilon (\gamma_\alpha - \gamma_\beta) L}{\hbar c},
\end{equation}
where $L$ is the baseline, and $E$ the neutrino energy. The \textbf{Riemann-zero term} predicts small, logarithmically spaced deviations in the oscillation pattern.

\section{Vacuum Energy Corrections}
The zero-point energy of the Hamiltonian crystal lattice receives a Riemann-zero contribution:
\begin{equation}
\rho_{\rm vac}^{(\mathcal{R})} = \frac{1}{V_H} \sum_n \frac{1}{2} \left( \Delta E_n + \epsilon \gamma_n \right)
= \rho_{\rm vac} + \frac{\epsilon}{2 V_H} \sum_n \gamma_n.
\end{equation}
These tiny fluctuations provide a \textbf{testable signature} in precision Casimir-effect or cosmological observations.

\section{Experimental Predictions}

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Neutrino oscillations:} Phase shifts of order $\Delta \phi \sim \epsilon \gamma_n L/(\hbar c)$ produce deviations in long-baseline experiments (DUNE, T2K). Predictable patterns correspond to the first few $\gamma_n$ values.
    \item \textbf{Vacuum energy fluctuations:} Low-amplitude oscillations $\Delta \Lambda / \Lambda \sim 10^{-15}-10^{-12}$ may appear in table-top dynamical Casimir or precision atomic interferometry experiments.
    \item \textbf{Photon–dark sector transitions:} Small Riemann-induced energy shifts modify portal-mediated photon emission rates in optical cavities.
\end{itemize}

\section{Discussion}
Embedding the Riemann zeros provides a \textbf{quantifiable, falsifiable} extension to the Hamiltonian crystal. All predicted deviations are small but systematic, and their detection would directly probe the underlying lattice structure of vacuum and the number-theoretic structure of fundamental physics.

\section{Conclusions}
The \textbf{Riemann-zero Hamiltonian crystal} introduces an elegant bridge between the zeta function and particle physics. Experimental tests in neutrino oscillations, vacuum-energy modulation, and portal-induced photon dynamics could validate this framework and potentially reveal subtle patterns dictated by the Riemann zeros.

